WEBVTT

00:01.349 --> 00:02.915
- Previously on
"God Friended Me"...

00:02.959 --> 00:04.221
- The Fibonacci ratio.

00:04.265 --> 00:06.354
It is the most mysterious
mathematical concept

00:06.397 --> 00:07.572
in all of nature.

00:07.616 --> 00:09.487
Falken is definitely behind
the God Account.

00:09.531 --> 00:11.011
- Wait, you know Falken's
real name?

00:11.054 --> 00:13.361
- What was it?
- Henry Chase.

00:13.404 --> 00:15.232
- I couldn't help but notice
you and Miles talking.

00:15.276 --> 00:16.668
- He seems to have changed.

00:16.712 --> 00:17.974
- And it's pretty obvious
what's causing it.

00:18.018 --> 00:19.584
- Not the God Account.

00:19.628 --> 00:21.325
- I'm actually back together
with Eli.

00:21.369 --> 00:22.587
Things with him are good.

00:22.631 --> 00:24.285
How do you guys
know each other?

00:24.328 --> 00:26.504
- Nia was the DJ that kept
covering up my posters.

00:26.548 --> 00:28.158
We both ended up in that
marketing class.

00:28.202 --> 00:30.334
Dad, hey.
Is everything all right?

00:30.378 --> 00:35.252
- I'd like to know a little bit
more about this God Account.

00:36.514 --> 00:39.474
[upbeat music]

00:39.517 --> 00:44.653
♪

00:44.696 --> 00:46.959
- Dad came by my apartment
last night.

00:47.003 --> 00:49.179
Wanted to know all about the
God Account and how it works.

00:49.223 --> 00:50.572
- Are you serious?
- Mm-hmm.

00:50.615 --> 00:52.661
- How'd it go?

00:52.704 --> 00:56.186
- I explained it to him, and
after a long period of silence

00:56.230 --> 00:58.014
he said there had to be
an explanation

00:58.058 --> 01:00.973
and whoever was behind the God
Account is clearly not God.

01:01.017 --> 01:03.063
- Well, at least you both
agree on that.

01:03.106 --> 01:04.977
- After he got over
the initial shock,

01:05.021 --> 01:08.242
he said he was happy
that I was making a difference.

01:09.330 --> 01:11.636
But I could tell it was a lot
for him to take in.

01:11.680 --> 01:14.161
- Maybe you should show him
firsthand.

01:14.204 --> 01:15.640
You know, take him on one
of your Friend Suggestions.

01:15.684 --> 01:16.772
Like a "Friend Along."

01:16.815 --> 01:18.687
- Oh--[chuckles]
Wait. Wait.

01:18.730 --> 01:21.081
Let's not get crazy.
One step at a time.

01:21.124 --> 01:22.212
- I just have to make
a quick stop,

01:22.256 --> 01:23.866
pick up something
for Dee.

01:26.651 --> 01:27.652
[door bell rings]

01:29.393 --> 01:31.265
Here we go.

01:31.308 --> 01:34.790
Nothing says love
like a $40 eyeliner.

01:34.833 --> 01:36.835
- Obviously.

01:36.879 --> 01:39.621
- So what about you? How are
things going with you and Nia?

01:41.405 --> 01:42.928
- Good.

01:42.972 --> 01:44.974
- Look at that smile,

01:45.017 --> 01:46.628
Things must be going
better than good.

01:46.671 --> 01:48.369
- I have to admit.

01:48.412 --> 01:50.022
She is the first girl
in a while

01:50.066 --> 01:51.763
that I can see myself
being with.

01:51.807 --> 01:53.852
- I'm happy for you.

01:53.896 --> 01:55.506
- Hold it right there,
little girl.

01:55.550 --> 01:57.160
You got something
in your bag?

01:57.204 --> 01:59.902
- Yes. That's what backpacks
are used for.

01:59.945 --> 02:01.382
To hold things.
- Okay, don't be smart.

02:01.425 --> 02:03.340
I just watched you steal
that bottle of perfume.

02:03.384 --> 02:05.168
Open the bag.

02:07.127 --> 02:08.345
- Fine.

02:11.914 --> 02:13.524
- I'm calling the cops.
- Please don't!

02:13.568 --> 02:15.961
- Whoa--wait, wait, wait.
Hold on. That's not necessary.

02:16.005 --> 02:18.225
- Excuse me?
- Well, she's just a kid.

02:18.268 --> 02:20.183
- Can't we just
figure something out?

02:20.227 --> 02:22.838
- Look, you, uh,
work on commission, right?

02:22.881 --> 02:24.883
- Yeah?
- Okay, so how about I pay

02:24.927 --> 02:26.189
for the perfume
and we call it a day?

02:29.149 --> 02:30.933
- Fine.
- Thanks.

02:30.976 --> 02:32.848
- You're... wel--

02:32.891 --> 02:37.461
- That'll be $125 plus tax.
I'll ring you up.

02:37.505 --> 02:39.898
- Seriously?

02:39.942 --> 02:41.552
- I'm proud of you.

02:41.596 --> 02:43.946
Helping people even when the
God Account isn't behind it.

02:43.989 --> 02:47.863
- Yeah, but the God Account
has never cost me $125,

02:47.906 --> 02:49.560
- So how's work going?

02:49.604 --> 02:52.911
- It's good. Yeah, Natalie
loved my chess story.

02:52.955 --> 02:54.783
Said she's making a decision
about the job

02:54.826 --> 02:56.263
in Features next week.

02:56.306 --> 02:57.612
- Ah, you're gonna get it.

02:59.657 --> 03:00.832
- Thanks.

03:02.051 --> 03:04.227
Yeah, I'm really proud
of what I've been doing.

03:04.271 --> 03:05.924
I mean, I've met
some amazing people.

03:05.968 --> 03:08.710
- Yeah, and thank God
for Miles, right?

03:08.753 --> 03:10.494
- Your point being?

03:10.538 --> 03:12.192
- I'm just saying you guys
have been spending

03:12.235 --> 03:13.584
a lot of time together lately

03:13.628 --> 03:15.760
and sometimes I wonder
if I should have

03:15.804 --> 03:17.197
anything to worry about.

03:17.240 --> 03:18.850
- There is nothing
to worry about.

03:20.156 --> 03:21.592
Look, I know I've been busy

03:21.636 --> 03:24.508
and we haven't spent a lot
of time together, so--

03:24.552 --> 03:26.684
Why don't we change that?

03:26.728 --> 03:28.338
- I'm listening.

03:28.382 --> 03:29.818
- Well, my friend was telling
me about this really great

03:29.861 --> 03:31.385
bed and breakfast in Vermont.

03:31.428 --> 03:34.344
We could drive up tomorrow
and spend the weekend.

03:34.388 --> 03:36.520
- Okay,
that sounds perfect.

03:36.564 --> 03:39.044
I'll, uh, rent a car
and pack my bags.

03:39.088 --> 03:41.090
- Can't wait.

03:42.787 --> 03:44.485
- Now that we know
Falken's real name

03:44.528 --> 03:46.269
is Henry Chase,
what did you find?

03:46.313 --> 03:47.879
- Nothing.

03:47.923 --> 03:50.055
- You're telling me you weren't
able to find anything?

03:50.099 --> 03:51.579
- Nothing.

03:51.622 --> 03:53.581
No birth certificate,
driver's license, bank account.

03:53.624 --> 03:56.105
And I've seen people scrub
the Internet before,

03:56.148 --> 03:58.586
but not like this.

03:58.629 --> 04:01.023
- Are you sure you don't
recognize the name Henry Chase?

04:01.066 --> 04:02.503
- No. Why?

04:02.546 --> 04:04.200
- Well, because if he is behind
the God Account,

04:04.244 --> 04:06.246
then there must be
some connection.

04:06.289 --> 04:08.248
A reason why he chose you.

04:08.291 --> 04:10.424
- If there is, I wouldn't know
what it would be.

04:10.467 --> 04:11.947
- [sighs]

04:11.990 --> 04:13.905
There's got to be something
we're missing.

04:13.949 --> 04:15.907
What else do you know
about him?

04:15.951 --> 04:18.562
- Not much. People think he was
a Computer Science major

04:18.606 --> 04:20.347
at Columbia, but I couldn't
find any enrollment

04:20.390 --> 04:22.392
for him online.

04:22.436 --> 04:25.177
- Which is why
we need to go offline.

04:25.221 --> 04:27.441
Universities always have
a paper trail

04:27.484 --> 04:29.965
and a guy that smart would've
published in school journals.

04:30.008 --> 04:31.445
We need to head down there.

04:31.488 --> 04:33.577
Search through
the Columbia library.

04:33.621 --> 04:35.840
- [scoffs]
What, like card catalogs?

04:35.884 --> 04:37.451
- No, she's right.

04:37.494 --> 04:38.669
It's one thing for Falken
to sit behind a computer

04:38.713 --> 04:40.497
and press a few buttons.

04:40.541 --> 04:42.064
It's another thing for him
to go out into the real world

04:42.107 --> 04:44.936
and remove every piece
of paper from existence.

04:44.980 --> 04:48.244
♪

04:48.288 --> 04:49.941
- Well, when you put it
like that...

04:49.985 --> 04:51.813
[cell phone buzzes and chimes]

04:54.163 --> 04:55.860
- I got
a new Friend Suggestion.

04:55.904 --> 04:57.993
Aaron Booker.

04:58.036 --> 05:00.474
Look, he's a member
of my dad's church.

05:00.517 --> 05:02.432
♪

05:02.476 --> 05:05.435
- I feel like Falken knows
we're getting really close

05:05.479 --> 05:07.394
and he's just trying
to get you distracted.

05:07.437 --> 05:08.525
- Well, that's why
I have you two.

05:08.569 --> 05:09.961
You head down
to the library.

05:10.005 --> 05:11.615
I'll go ask my dad about
Aaron Booker,

05:11.659 --> 05:12.921
see what I can find out.

05:12.964 --> 05:18.970
♪

05:20.755 --> 05:22.060
Dad.

05:22.104 --> 05:23.714
- Miles.
- Hey.

05:23.758 --> 05:27.979
Um, I, uh--just stopped by
to talk to you.

05:29.198 --> 05:31.548
About the God Account.

05:31.592 --> 05:34.203
- You know, I appreciate you
walking me through all of that.

05:34.246 --> 05:36.988
Um, I figured I'd have
a little bit more time

05:37.032 --> 05:38.512
to digest things.

05:38.555 --> 05:40.383
- Oh, I completely
understand,

05:40.427 --> 05:43.995
and I wouldn't have brought
it up again, but

05:44.039 --> 05:47.912
I got a new Friend Suggestion
this morning and...

05:49.392 --> 05:51.481
He's a member
of Harlem Episcopal.

05:51.525 --> 05:57.835
♪

05:57.879 --> 05:59.620
- Yeah,
I know Aaron very well.

05:59.663 --> 06:02.623
As a matter of fact, um...

06:02.666 --> 06:04.059
He came to see me
earlier today.

06:04.102 --> 06:05.408
- About what?

06:05.452 --> 06:07.149
- I'm sorry, Miles.
I can't tell you that.

06:07.192 --> 06:09.847
There is a confidentiality
between pastor and parishioner.

06:09.891 --> 06:11.458
I have an ethical obligation

06:11.501 --> 06:13.503
to keep those conversations
private.

06:13.547 --> 06:15.462
- Of course. No, of course.
I understand.

06:15.505 --> 06:17.420
- But don't you think
the timing

06:17.464 --> 06:19.161
for all of this
is a bit strange?

06:19.204 --> 06:20.467
I mean, the day after we have
a conversation

06:20.510 --> 06:21.946
about the God Account,

06:21.990 --> 06:23.557
they send you a name
of one of my parishioners?

06:23.600 --> 06:25.602
- Dad, I'm way past strange

06:25.646 --> 06:27.474
when it comes to
the God Account.

06:31.826 --> 06:34.524
- Hey--look, wait. Um...

06:36.047 --> 06:39.442
I can't tell you why he came
to see me, but

06:39.486 --> 06:41.705
about six months ago,
his wife died.

06:41.749 --> 06:43.751
I presided over the funeral.

06:43.794 --> 06:46.144
She was an extraordinary woman

06:46.188 --> 06:50.453
and her loss hit him hard.

06:50.497 --> 06:51.498
Like it would anyone.

06:51.541 --> 06:53.674
♪

06:53.717 --> 06:56.416
- Do you mind
if I talk to him?

06:57.504 --> 07:00.158
- Miles, I've been counseling
my parishioners for 25 years.

07:00.202 --> 07:02.160
- I--I know, but maybe
there's something going on

07:02.204 --> 07:04.511
in Aaron's life that
he's not sharing with you.

07:04.554 --> 07:06.687
That's you're not seeing.
Dad!

07:06.730 --> 07:08.950
♪

07:08.993 --> 07:10.908
I just want to help.

07:10.952 --> 07:12.649
- I understand that.

07:12.693 --> 07:17.132
But in this case, I'm going to
ask you to respect his privacy

07:17.175 --> 07:18.873
and my wishes.

07:18.916 --> 07:22.529
Please do not get involved.

07:22.572 --> 07:27.925
♪

07:35.280 --> 07:38.240
[soft music]

07:38.283 --> 07:39.633
♪

07:39.676 --> 07:41.243
- Cara, this is gonna take
an eternity to go through.

07:41.286 --> 07:42.462
- [scoffs]
The digital age

07:42.505 --> 07:43.941
has made you lazy,
Rakesh.

07:43.985 --> 07:45.987
We've only been at it for,
like, an hour.

07:46.030 --> 07:48.816
You know, this is how Woodward
and Bernstein broke Watergate.

07:48.859 --> 07:51.949
Good old fashioned
investigative work.

07:51.993 --> 07:53.908
- That's the last of
the computer science journals

07:53.951 --> 07:56.867
from 1999 to 2003.

07:56.911 --> 08:00.871
♪

08:00.915 --> 08:04.309
If there's anything else
I can do for you, anything,

08:04.353 --> 08:06.224
just, uh, let me know.

08:06.268 --> 08:07.574
- Thank you.

08:07.617 --> 08:09.750
♪

08:09.793 --> 08:11.447
- [chuckles]
Just to be clear.

08:11.491 --> 08:15.364
If he was a she, I'd totally
use my charm to get access.

08:15.407 --> 08:18.541
- Would you?
Hmm.

08:18.585 --> 08:20.674
- Hey, you two find anything?

08:20.717 --> 08:22.545
- Uh, no. Not yet.

08:22.589 --> 08:24.634
But if there is anything
in here about Falken,

08:24.678 --> 08:25.983
we'll find it.
What about you?

08:26.027 --> 08:27.419
You find anything
on Aaron Booker?

08:27.463 --> 08:28.856
- No, and when I asked
my dad about him,

08:28.899 --> 08:29.857
he told me to back off.

08:29.900 --> 08:31.423
- Why?

08:31.467 --> 08:33.164
- He doesn't want me
interfering

08:33.208 --> 08:35.776
with any of the members
of his church and honestly,

08:35.819 --> 08:38.213
I see where he's coming from.

08:38.256 --> 08:41.042
- Yeah but the God Account sent
you Aaron's name for a reason.

08:42.783 --> 08:45.350
- Uh, guys?

08:45.394 --> 08:47.396
I think I just
hit the jackpot.

08:47.439 --> 08:51.139
Written by the one and only
Henry Chase.

08:51.182 --> 08:53.663
The article's about
predictive analytics.

08:53.707 --> 08:55.883
Man, Falken was decades ahead
of his time.

08:55.926 --> 08:57.667
He was writing about
the advancements in AI

08:57.711 --> 08:59.800
that we're only beginning
to delve into today.

08:59.843 --> 09:01.279
- That's all well and good,
Rakesh,

09:01.323 --> 09:03.020
but we need actual information
on him.

09:03.064 --> 09:04.413
His theories are not gonna
help us

09:04.456 --> 09:05.719
figure out where he is now.
- Yeah, she's right.

09:05.762 --> 09:07.242
We need something personal.

09:07.285 --> 09:08.765
- Exactly.

09:08.809 --> 09:11.202
♪

09:11.246 --> 09:13.596
When I was at Ohio State,
I wrote for "The Lantern."

09:13.640 --> 09:16.077
We would do profiles
on students all the time.

09:16.120 --> 09:19.515
Maybe their school paper
did the same thing?

09:19.559 --> 09:23.693
- Okay, great idea. Uh, I'll go
ask lover boy over there

09:23.737 --> 09:26.174
to help us, uh,
pull any old newspapers

09:26.217 --> 09:27.523
from when Henry Chase
was here.

09:27.567 --> 09:29.525
♪

09:29.569 --> 09:32.267
- So what are you gonna do
about Aaron?

09:32.310 --> 09:34.051
- I think you're right.
I need to talk to him.

09:34.095 --> 09:35.749
If there's something
I can help him with,

09:35.792 --> 09:37.620
I have to trust that my dad
will understand.

09:37.664 --> 09:40.101
♪

09:40.144 --> 09:41.232
Call me if you
two find anything?

09:41.276 --> 09:43.060
- Yeah.

09:43.104 --> 09:45.497
[bell rings]
- Hey, Dad.

09:47.674 --> 09:49.980
I was wondering
when I'd be seeing you.

09:50.024 --> 09:51.939
Miles called me
after you two talked.

09:51.982 --> 09:53.593
Filled me in.

09:53.636 --> 09:57.031
- I see. Then I supposed
he told you that his, um,

09:57.074 --> 09:58.946
Friend Suggestion is a member
of my congregation?

09:58.989 --> 10:00.382
- He did.

10:00.425 --> 10:01.949
- I am responsible
for the well-being

10:01.992 --> 10:03.690
of my parishioners.

10:03.733 --> 10:05.909
I can't have some stranger
intruding in their lives.

10:05.953 --> 10:08.042
- Miles is not a stranger, Dad.

10:11.436 --> 10:14.701
- I recognize the good that
your brother is doing

10:14.744 --> 10:18.922
and, of course, I want him out
in the world helping people.

10:18.966 --> 10:20.489
I just wish...

10:20.532 --> 10:21.925
- What?

10:21.969 --> 10:24.711
- It was done for reasons
that were...

10:26.713 --> 10:28.192
Closer to home.

10:28.236 --> 10:31.065
- You mean God
and not the God Account.

10:31.108 --> 10:32.675
- Yes.

10:32.719 --> 10:36.157
At least then
we'd have something...

10:36.200 --> 10:37.593
we can share together.

10:37.637 --> 10:40.814
- Maybe this is a chance
to do that.

10:40.857 --> 10:42.293
See it firsthand.

10:42.337 --> 10:44.295
Look, I think if you do,
you'll see more of you

10:44.339 --> 10:46.123
rubbed off on him
than you think.

10:46.167 --> 10:48.343
- Maybe you're right.

10:52.086 --> 10:54.218
I recognize that scarf.

10:55.524 --> 10:57.918
- It was Mom's favorite.
- Hmm.

10:57.961 --> 10:59.702
♪

10:59.746 --> 11:02.139
- It'll be 17 years next week.

11:02.183 --> 11:04.707
- I can't believe
it's been that long.

11:04.751 --> 11:06.230
- Miles' Friend Suggestion--

11:06.274 --> 11:08.798
he lost his wife
a few months back.

11:08.842 --> 11:10.365
- Yeah?

11:10.408 --> 11:13.368
- Did you ever think
that maybe the God Account

11:13.411 --> 11:15.196
sent Miles
your parishioner's name

11:15.239 --> 11:17.111
because they know that

11:17.154 --> 11:19.156
you could use a little extra
help with this one?

11:19.200 --> 11:26.207
♪

11:27.338 --> 11:28.905
[knocking on door]

11:31.473 --> 11:35.129
- Can I help you?
- Hey I'm Miles Finer.

11:35.172 --> 11:36.870
Reverend Finer's son.

11:36.913 --> 11:40.003
- Oh, yes, of course.
Uh, what can I do for you?

11:40.047 --> 11:44.747
- If you have a few minutes,
I was hoping we could talk.

11:44.791 --> 11:46.662
- Sure. Come on in.

11:49.578 --> 11:51.101
I'm just finishing up dinner.

11:51.145 --> 11:53.625
- It smells great.
- Thank you.

11:53.669 --> 11:56.193
Since my wife passed, I've had
to learn a few new skills.

11:56.237 --> 11:57.847
Cooking included.

11:57.891 --> 12:00.284
Hasn't come easy but I think
I'm getting the hang of it.

12:00.328 --> 12:02.896
- Yeah, my--my dad mentioned
that your wife passed

12:02.939 --> 12:04.724
a few months ago.

12:04.767 --> 12:06.682
I'm sorry to hear
about your loss.

12:06.726 --> 12:08.075
- Thank you.

12:08.118 --> 12:09.685
- Yeah, I--I know
when my mom died,

12:09.729 --> 12:12.122
every day seemed to have
its own challenges.

12:12.166 --> 12:13.863
So I thought I would reach out

12:13.907 --> 12:17.301
and see if there was anything
I could help you with.

12:17.345 --> 12:19.695
- The apple doesn't fall
far from the tree.

12:19.739 --> 12:20.827
Thank you, Miles,

12:20.870 --> 12:23.960
but we're doing pretty good.

12:24.004 --> 12:26.615
- We?
- Yes, my daughter and I.

12:26.658 --> 12:30.924
Hanna! Dinner!

12:30.967 --> 12:36.581
♪

12:36.625 --> 12:39.628
Uh, you--you two
know each other?

12:39.671 --> 12:42.196
- You could say that.

12:42.239 --> 12:44.502
- Dad, I can explain.

12:44.546 --> 12:45.765
- Explain what?

12:45.808 --> 12:48.593
♪

12:55.470 --> 12:56.993
- Hanna told me what happened.
Thank you

12:57.037 --> 12:59.517
for stepping in
at the store, Miles.

12:59.561 --> 13:01.693
The last thing that I need
right now is to have

13:01.737 --> 13:03.478
my daughter getting arrested
for shoplifting.

13:03.521 --> 13:04.827
- Of course.

13:04.871 --> 13:05.828
- And I insist
on paying you back.

13:05.872 --> 13:07.395
How much do I owe you?

13:07.438 --> 13:08.396
- No, no, no, no.
Please, please, please.

13:08.439 --> 13:09.919
I didn't come here for that.

13:11.616 --> 13:13.923
I lost my mom
when I was a kid too.

13:13.967 --> 13:15.838
So I know what
she's going through,

13:15.882 --> 13:18.145
how easy it is to act out.

13:18.188 --> 13:20.538
- I wish I could say
it was the first time,

13:20.582 --> 13:21.931
but after my wife passed away,

13:21.975 --> 13:23.890
Hanna started getting
into fights at school,

13:23.933 --> 13:27.154
her grades dropped.
I had to pull her out.

13:27.197 --> 13:29.112
I took a leave from work
so I could homeschool.

13:29.156 --> 13:30.766
- Has she talked to anyone?

13:30.810 --> 13:33.421
- Well, your father recommended
a family therapist,

13:33.464 --> 13:36.511
but she refused to go
and I didn't want to push.

13:36.554 --> 13:39.296
- Well, it sounds like you're
doing everything you can.

13:39.340 --> 13:42.778
- I am.
I've tried to keep her busy.

13:42.822 --> 13:44.867
Take her to her favorite spots
around the city.

13:44.911 --> 13:46.564
It's just everywhere we go--

13:46.608 --> 13:50.960
- Is a reminder
of what she lost.

13:51.004 --> 13:52.744
- Lately I'm thinking
your dad is right.

13:52.788 --> 13:54.224
♪

13:54.268 --> 13:56.357
- About what?

13:56.400 --> 14:01.188
- It might be easier--
take less time for Hanna--

14:01.231 --> 14:03.930
if we started over.

14:03.973 --> 14:06.323
Move to a new city.
Started making new memories.

14:06.367 --> 14:08.412
- My father said that?

14:08.456 --> 14:11.198
- He said that I should do
what I feel is best for Hanna.

14:11.241 --> 14:13.200
And after today,

14:13.243 --> 14:15.855
I'm more convinced
than ever he's right.

14:15.898 --> 14:22.862
♪

14:26.474 --> 14:29.912
- [giggling]

14:29.956 --> 14:32.828
What?

14:32.872 --> 14:34.134
- You know, this'll go
a whole lot faster

14:34.177 --> 14:35.309
if I'm not
the only one looking.

14:35.352 --> 14:37.050
- Sorry, sorry.

14:37.093 --> 14:40.531
Um, Jaya just texted asking
if I knew what ice fishing was.

14:40.575 --> 14:42.098
- Do you?

14:42.142 --> 14:44.840
- No, but it sounds hilarious.

14:44.884 --> 14:46.233
- It seems like
you two are making

14:46.276 --> 14:47.451
the whole long distance
thing work.

14:47.495 --> 14:50.585
- Yeah. It's tough.

14:50.628 --> 14:52.413
I guess the one good thing is

14:52.456 --> 14:54.415
it confirmed what I've known
since our first date.

14:54.458 --> 14:55.764
- What's that?

14:55.807 --> 14:57.505
- That she's the one.

15:00.247 --> 15:02.162
Is that how you felt when Eli
came back in your life?

15:02.205 --> 15:05.295
♪

15:05.339 --> 15:07.558
- I mean,
I definitely feel like

15:07.602 --> 15:10.779
the universe wanted us
to find each other again.

15:10.822 --> 15:12.302
- Did you want to find him?

15:12.346 --> 15:19.353
♪

15:20.789 --> 15:22.051
Falken?

15:22.095 --> 15:23.357
- Excuse me?

15:23.400 --> 15:26.012
♪

15:26.055 --> 15:29.624
- It's an article
from 15 years ago.

15:29.667 --> 15:31.931
- Henry Chase.
Okay, turn to page 12.

15:31.974 --> 15:38.938
♪

15:38.981 --> 15:42.071
- Um, we have a problem.

15:42.115 --> 15:43.203
- What?

15:43.246 --> 15:44.682
- There is no page 12.

15:44.726 --> 15:47.163
♪

15:47.207 --> 15:48.599
- Someone ripped it out?

15:48.643 --> 15:49.992
- Oh, got to hand it to him.

15:50.036 --> 15:52.255
Falken's covered his tracks
offline as well.

15:52.299 --> 15:54.562
- Whatever is in that article
must've been important.

15:54.605 --> 15:56.042
- What do we do now?

15:56.085 --> 16:02.439
♪

16:02.483 --> 16:04.137
- A list of contributors.

16:04.180 --> 16:05.921
One of these students
must've written the article

16:05.965 --> 16:07.575
about Henry Chase.

16:07.618 --> 16:09.055
If I can track them down,

16:09.098 --> 16:10.882
maybe they can tell us
what it was about.

16:10.926 --> 16:14.103
♪

16:19.630 --> 16:20.980
- Got a minute?

16:22.329 --> 16:23.634
- Aaron called me last night

16:23.678 --> 16:25.114
and he told me
that you stopped by.

16:25.158 --> 16:26.594
- I did.

16:26.637 --> 16:28.857
- Aaron and Hanna need
to deal with this as a family.

16:28.900 --> 16:31.338
- Dad, how is moving away
dealing with it?

16:31.381 --> 16:32.426
- When your mother died,

16:32.469 --> 16:33.688
I thought of doing
the same thing.

16:33.731 --> 16:35.124
There is nothing wrong
with a fresh start.

16:35.168 --> 16:36.952
- There is if you're
just running away

16:36.996 --> 16:38.388
from your problems.

16:40.912 --> 16:42.218
- What's that supposed to mean?

16:43.132 --> 16:44.568
[cell phone buzzes and chimes]

16:47.571 --> 16:50.096
♪

16:50.139 --> 16:51.358
- What?

16:51.401 --> 16:53.316
- The God Account
just liked Paul's Daughter.

16:53.360 --> 16:54.752
It's that restaurant
on Coney Island.

16:54.796 --> 16:56.798
- Hm.

16:56.841 --> 16:58.104
- I think we need
to go down there.

16:58.147 --> 16:59.322
It may have something
to do with Aaron.

16:59.366 --> 17:00.976
- How do you know?

17:01.977 --> 17:03.239
- I don't.

17:03.283 --> 17:05.589
And I know it might
sound crazy,

17:05.633 --> 17:06.938
but that's the thing
about the God Account.

17:06.982 --> 17:08.462
It never does anything
without a purpose.

17:08.505 --> 17:10.203
Even if you can't see it
at first.

17:10.246 --> 17:11.987
♪

17:12.031 --> 17:14.033
- Sounds like you're talking
about faith.

17:14.076 --> 17:16.078
- No. No, no, no.
I'm talking about proof.

17:16.122 --> 17:18.080
Okay?
This has happened before.

17:18.124 --> 17:20.256
I know this place.

17:20.300 --> 17:22.998
I need to get down there
and...

17:24.130 --> 17:26.436
I want you to come with me.

17:26.480 --> 17:28.569
Look, we'll check it out.

17:28.612 --> 17:30.875
If there's nothing there,

17:30.919 --> 17:34.227
I'll drop it.

17:34.270 --> 17:37.230
[gentle music]

17:37.273 --> 17:38.796
- [Arthur laughing]

17:38.840 --> 17:42.104
I haven't been
to Coney Island in years.

17:42.148 --> 17:43.540
Nothing's changed.

17:43.584 --> 17:47.370
- That's what makes it great.
- Yeah.

17:47.414 --> 17:49.155
[screaming]

17:53.811 --> 17:54.899
- Everything okay?

17:54.943 --> 17:56.814
- Yeah, yeah.

17:59.165 --> 18:01.471
Mom used to take me here
for my birthday.

18:04.996 --> 18:06.911
I can still picture it
in my mind.

18:09.436 --> 18:11.655
- It'll be 17 years next week.

18:13.135 --> 18:14.223
- I know.

18:17.618 --> 18:20.969
- Paul's Daughter.
So what happens now?

18:21.012 --> 18:25.278
- Uh, I don't know
but we'll know when we see it.

18:25.321 --> 18:28.716
- I, uh, only have
a half an hour, Miles.

18:28.759 --> 18:32.067
I've--I've got to set up
for an afternoon service.

18:32.111 --> 18:35.201
[indistinct chatter]

18:39.161 --> 18:42.947
♪

18:42.991 --> 18:44.384
- Hanna.

18:44.427 --> 18:48.301
♪

18:48.344 --> 18:49.867
- I don't understand.

18:49.911 --> 18:51.173
I mean, how would they know
she was gonna be here?

18:51.217 --> 18:52.392
- I--I don't know,

18:52.435 --> 18:53.523
but that's the thing
about the God Account.

18:53.567 --> 18:55.308
Sometimes things like this
just happen.

18:55.351 --> 18:57.397
♪

18:57.440 --> 18:58.789
- Um...

19:01.314 --> 19:03.403
I don't see her father
so I should give Aaron a call.

19:03.446 --> 19:05.318
- Wait--wait--wait a minute.
Let me--

19:05.361 --> 19:08.016
Let me talk to her first.
See what's going on.

19:08.059 --> 19:09.496
♪

19:09.539 --> 19:10.975
- Uh...

19:13.282 --> 19:14.675
All right.

19:14.718 --> 19:20.289
♪

19:20.333 --> 19:21.899
- W-what are you doing here?

19:21.943 --> 19:24.467
- Just taking a walk
with my dad. You?

19:24.511 --> 19:27.166
- Same. He's grabbing
some food for us.

19:27.209 --> 19:29.124
He'll be back in a second.

19:29.864 --> 19:32.345
- You, uh, mind if I chill
with you until he comes back?

19:33.302 --> 19:34.651
- Whatever.

19:44.357 --> 19:45.967
- Everything okay?

19:46.968 --> 19:48.796
- We're moving.

19:48.839 --> 19:50.798
He brought me here
to break the news.

19:50.841 --> 19:52.800
Like a hot dog
and some Skee-Ball

19:52.843 --> 19:55.498
will magically
make things better.

19:55.542 --> 19:57.761
- You don't want to move?

19:57.805 --> 20:00.155
- No.

20:00.199 --> 20:01.852
- Did you tell him that?

20:01.896 --> 20:03.637
- I can't.

20:03.680 --> 20:04.768
- Why?

20:06.770 --> 20:08.207
- You wouldn't understand.

20:10.600 --> 20:13.386
- Trust me.
I would better than most.

20:17.216 --> 20:19.261
My mom died when I was 8.

20:19.305 --> 20:20.958
♪

20:21.002 --> 20:22.656
And believe me,
there are things I wish

20:22.699 --> 20:24.832
I would've told my dad
back then.

20:24.875 --> 20:27.443
♪

20:27.487 --> 20:31.055
If I could change it,

20:31.099 --> 20:32.274
I would.

20:32.318 --> 20:33.884
♪

20:33.928 --> 20:35.756
- Arthur?
- Oh, hey.

20:35.799 --> 20:38.672
- Hey. [chuckles]
What are you doing here?

20:38.715 --> 20:41.196
- Uh, I'm just here with Miles.
We came across Hanna.

20:41.240 --> 20:43.720
Just wanted to make sure
she was okay.

20:43.764 --> 20:45.635
- Hanna?

20:47.333 --> 20:49.509
- Your dad needs to know
how you feel

20:49.552 --> 20:51.598
before it's too late.

20:56.298 --> 20:58.300
- I'm ready to go.

20:58.344 --> 21:01.042
- Everything okay?
- Fine. Can we go?

21:01.085 --> 21:02.696
- Hanna, I think you need
to tell your dad.

21:04.872 --> 21:06.308
- Tell me what?

21:06.352 --> 21:07.744
- I don't know
what he's talking about.

21:07.788 --> 21:10.660
- Miles, what's going on?

21:18.102 --> 21:20.017
- Hanna doesn't want to move.

21:22.281 --> 21:23.717
- Is that true?

21:23.760 --> 21:25.545
- No.
- Hanna.

21:25.588 --> 21:29.157
- I don't even know you.
Just leave me alone.

21:29.200 --> 21:31.028
Can we just go, please?

21:31.072 --> 21:32.639
- Yeah, of course,
sweetie.

21:32.682 --> 21:34.554
Look, I don't know what
you were talking about

21:34.597 --> 21:36.686
with my daughter but I think
you need to stay away from us.

21:38.819 --> 21:40.168
Good-bye, Arthur.

21:43.650 --> 21:45.086
- You want to tell me
what the hell just happened?

21:45.129 --> 21:46.914
- I was just trying to help.

21:46.957 --> 21:48.481
- It didn't look like
that to me.

21:48.524 --> 21:51.005
I mean, Aaron knows
what's best for his child.

21:51.048 --> 21:53.921
- How would you know?
You never did.

21:53.964 --> 21:57.620
♪

21:57.664 --> 21:58.882
- Excuse me?

21:58.926 --> 21:59.927
- Nothing.
It doesn't matter.

21:59.970 --> 22:01.102
- Clearly, it does.

22:01.145 --> 22:05.106
♪

22:05.149 --> 22:08.022
- Mom always brought me here
for my birthday.

22:08.065 --> 22:09.850
- I remember.
- And every year,

22:09.893 --> 22:11.678
I would run up to the Cyclone

22:11.721 --> 22:13.636
and measure myself to see

22:13.680 --> 22:16.160
if I was tall enough
to finally ride it.

22:16.204 --> 22:19.686
And on my eighth birthday,
I got close.

22:19.729 --> 22:22.689
So I knew it was only
one year left.

22:22.732 --> 22:26.083
Only Mom didn't make it
to my ninth birthday.

22:26.127 --> 22:28.695
But I promised myself

22:28.738 --> 22:30.044
that I was gonna ride it

22:30.087 --> 22:32.568
because that's what Mom
wanted me to do.

22:32.612 --> 22:34.875
But it never happened.

22:34.918 --> 22:37.138
♪

22:37.181 --> 22:38.792
'Cause you never took me.

22:38.835 --> 22:42.012
♪

22:42.056 --> 22:45.102
- I didn't realize

22:45.146 --> 22:47.409
how much you
still wanted to go.

22:47.453 --> 22:49.324
- Well, if you were around,
you would know,

22:49.368 --> 22:51.282
but you weren't.

22:51.326 --> 22:52.893
- What are you talking about?
Of course I was.

22:52.936 --> 22:55.896
- Dad, after Mom died, you
disappeared into the church.

22:55.939 --> 22:57.767
And whenever we did talk,

22:57.811 --> 23:00.161
the only thing you would
tell me to do was have faith.

23:00.204 --> 23:03.469
I didn't need faith.
I needed my father.

23:03.512 --> 23:05.775
- Faith was the one thing
that got me through it.

23:05.819 --> 23:07.386
The one thing
that I knew could help,

23:07.429 --> 23:09.039
and I thought it could
help you as well.

23:09.083 --> 23:11.390
To know that God had a plan,

23:11.433 --> 23:13.261
even if you didn't understand--

23:13.304 --> 23:15.306
- Well, I guess God's plan
didn't involve

23:15.350 --> 23:17.134
taking a nine-year-old
to Coney Island

23:17.178 --> 23:19.093
for his birthday, did it?

23:19.136 --> 23:23.184
♪

23:23.227 --> 23:25.099
You know what I did
that night

23:25.142 --> 23:28.798
for the first time
in my life?

23:28.842 --> 23:32.411
I went to bed
without saying my prayers.

23:32.454 --> 23:35.805
And when I woke up
the next morning,

23:35.849 --> 23:40.462
I realized it didn't matter.

23:40.506 --> 23:42.812
Because nothing changed

23:42.856 --> 23:44.335
and it never did.

23:44.379 --> 23:51.386
♪

24:03.529 --> 24:05.705
- I can't believe you said
all that to Dad.

24:05.748 --> 24:08.359
- Yeah, it just
came tumbling out.

24:08.403 --> 24:10.840
I mean, we were in
such a good place.

24:10.884 --> 24:13.234
Like, why did I have
to bring this up now?

24:13.277 --> 24:15.236
It's not like
we can change the past.

24:15.279 --> 24:18.631
- No, no, no, Miles,
this is a big step for you.

24:18.674 --> 24:20.067
Dad needed to know
how you really thought

24:20.110 --> 24:21.416
after all these years.

24:21.460 --> 24:23.113
You needed to say it out loud.

24:23.157 --> 24:24.550
Get it off your chest.

24:24.593 --> 24:26.334
- Yeah, but aren't you supposed
to feel better

24:26.377 --> 24:27.727
after you do that?

24:27.770 --> 24:29.250
- Well, maybe
you don't feel better

24:29.293 --> 24:30.686
because you left before
you heard what he had to say.

24:33.428 --> 24:34.821
[sighs]

24:34.864 --> 24:36.997
Have you figured out
what Aaron might need?

24:37.040 --> 24:39.608
Why the God Account
sent you his name?

24:39.652 --> 24:40.914
- No.

24:40.957 --> 24:42.698
No, he seems to be okay.

24:44.004 --> 24:45.484
I think it's about Hanna.

24:47.224 --> 24:50.663
I'm just not sure
how to help her.

24:50.706 --> 24:55.972
♪

24:56.016 --> 24:57.539
- You're sure
this is the same student

24:57.583 --> 24:59.236
who wrote the profile
on Henry Chase?

24:59.280 --> 25:00.499
- Yeah, I spoke with her
last night.

25:00.542 --> 25:01.891
Her name's Pria Amar.

25:01.935 --> 25:03.327
She hasn't seen Henry
since college,

25:03.371 --> 25:05.242
but I convinced her
to meet with us.

25:05.286 --> 25:06.505
Hopefully she can
remember something

25:06.548 --> 25:07.680
that'll help us
find him.

25:07.723 --> 25:09.420
- Hmm, you're pretty good
at this.

25:09.464 --> 25:11.553
- Yeah, I know.
[chuckles]

25:11.597 --> 25:13.163
[cell phone buzzes and chimes]

25:13.207 --> 25:15.035
Hey.

25:15.078 --> 25:16.776
- Hey, the car is gassed,
Spotify playlist is queued.

25:16.819 --> 25:19.082
Any last minute requests
for snacks?

25:19.126 --> 25:20.780
- Uh, surprise me.

25:20.823 --> 25:22.433
- Okay, but you do realize

25:22.477 --> 25:23.870
that ends with gummy bears
and Reese's Pieces.

25:23.913 --> 25:25.567
- Okay, well maybe
just include a few items

25:25.611 --> 25:27.264
that aren't meant
to be eaten on Halloween?

25:27.308 --> 25:28.701
- [chuckles]

25:28.744 --> 25:30.224
So we're still good to go?

25:30.267 --> 25:31.573
- Uh, yeah, yeah.

25:31.617 --> 25:32.922
I just have to do
this interview

25:32.966 --> 25:34.141
and I'll meet you
in a few hours.

25:34.184 --> 25:37.057
- Okay.
[call ends]

25:37.100 --> 25:40.060
- Big move.
The weekend getaway.

25:40.103 --> 25:42.932
- Yeah. Yeah, I think
a big move is good.

25:42.976 --> 25:45.587
- Yeah?

25:45.631 --> 25:48.634
- What?
- We're friends now, right?

25:48.677 --> 25:50.331
- Well...
- [chuckles]

25:50.374 --> 25:52.159
- [laughs] Yes.

25:52.202 --> 25:54.596
- So, as a friend,

25:54.640 --> 25:57.425
can I ask you something?

25:57.468 --> 25:58.731
What are you doing?

25:58.774 --> 26:00.341
- Excuse me?

26:00.384 --> 26:03.039
- Cara, you were more excited
to spend the day at the library

26:03.083 --> 26:04.650
than you are to go on
this trip with Eli.

26:04.693 --> 26:07.261
- That's not true.

26:07.304 --> 26:10.481
- Look, a big move is for
telling someone how you feel,

26:10.525 --> 26:12.527
not convincing yourself.

26:12.571 --> 26:15.704
And you said that you felt like
the universe wanted you and Eli

26:15.748 --> 26:17.837
to meet again and--
and maybe that's true.

26:17.880 --> 26:20.579
But maybe it's not
for the reason you think.

26:24.060 --> 26:25.845
♪

26:25.888 --> 26:28.151
- Hey, I think that's her.

26:28.195 --> 26:30.632
♪

26:30.676 --> 26:32.025
You ready?

26:32.068 --> 26:33.679
- Woodward and Bernstein,
right?

26:33.722 --> 26:35.158
- [chuckles]

26:35.202 --> 26:40.207
♪

26:40.250 --> 26:42.035
Pria?

26:42.078 --> 26:44.254
- Cara?
It's nice to meet you.

26:44.298 --> 26:46.256
- Yeah, you too.
This is my friend Rakesh.

26:46.300 --> 26:48.650
- Hi.
- Nice to meet you.

26:48.694 --> 26:51.479
- I have to admit, I was pretty
surprised to get your call.

26:51.522 --> 26:52.654
You said you were looking
for Henry?

26:52.698 --> 26:54.569
- Um, yeah, uh--

26:54.613 --> 26:56.789
We were hoping he'd look
into this computer program

26:56.832 --> 26:59.356
we're having some
technical issues with.

26:59.400 --> 27:01.663
- I know you said that you
hadn't seen him since college,

27:01.707 --> 27:03.578
but do you guys keep in touch?

27:03.622 --> 27:05.536
- Sorry, no,
though I wished we had.

27:06.842 --> 27:08.365
- What can you tell us
about him?

27:08.409 --> 27:10.237
♪

27:10.280 --> 27:12.326
- Henry was different.

27:12.369 --> 27:14.763
Always... lost in thought.

27:14.807 --> 27:16.678
He used to walk around
the campus

27:16.722 --> 27:18.027
like he was just
passing through.

27:18.071 --> 27:20.029
It gave him this air
of mystery.

27:20.073 --> 27:21.727
Well, at least I thought so.

27:21.770 --> 27:23.772
Plus he was handsome
in a disheveled,

27:23.816 --> 27:25.774
who-the-hell-cares
kind of way.

27:25.818 --> 27:29.256
When I interviewed him,
he was talking about religion,

27:29.299 --> 27:31.301
philosophy, and computers
all at the same time.

27:31.345 --> 27:34.609
I just found myself nodding
trying to keep up.

27:34.653 --> 27:36.785
- Do you remember
if he had any friends?

27:36.829 --> 27:38.961
Any people he'd hang out with?

27:39.005 --> 27:42.399
- Not that I knew of.
He was quiet, kept to himself.

27:42.443 --> 27:43.836
- I know it's been a long time,

27:43.879 --> 27:46.490
but do you remember anything
from your article?

27:46.534 --> 27:49.755
Anything specific that might
help us track him down?

27:49.798 --> 27:52.496
- It's been 20 years.

27:52.540 --> 27:54.585
But lucky for you,

27:54.629 --> 27:57.588
I've kept the article I wrote.

27:57.632 --> 27:59.373
I was going to be a famous
journalist back then.

27:59.416 --> 28:01.331
I kept my early work
for posterity.

28:01.375 --> 28:03.638
- Did you end up
pursuing journalism?

28:03.682 --> 28:05.684
- No, somewhere along the way
to my Pulitzer,

28:05.727 --> 28:07.337
I feel in love
and settled down.

28:07.381 --> 28:09.731
Such is life.

28:09.775 --> 28:12.386
Would you do me a favor?

28:12.429 --> 28:15.955
If you find Henry, will you
tell him I said hello?

28:15.998 --> 28:18.305
- Sure.

28:18.348 --> 28:20.437
- Bye. Hope that helps.

28:20.481 --> 28:22.048
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

28:22.091 --> 28:26.574
♪

28:26.617 --> 28:28.358
- Dad?

28:28.402 --> 28:35.409
♪

28:54.950 --> 28:56.256
[knocking on door]

28:56.299 --> 28:58.084
♪

28:58.127 --> 28:59.781
- What are you doing here?

28:59.825 --> 29:02.305
- I'm sorry to bother you, but
if I can just talk with you.

29:02.349 --> 29:04.655
- Miles?

29:04.699 --> 29:06.570
- Dad, what's going on?

29:06.614 --> 29:09.225
- I came over to make sure
things were okay.

29:10.313 --> 29:13.273
- Look, Mr. Booker,
if I can just have five minutes

29:13.316 --> 29:15.188
of your time, please.

29:15.231 --> 29:17.930
It's about Hanna

29:17.973 --> 29:20.584
♪

29:20.628 --> 29:23.413
- I think you should listen
to what he has to say.

29:23.457 --> 29:26.982
♪

29:27.026 --> 29:28.592
- Five minutes.

29:28.636 --> 29:34.076
♪

29:34.120 --> 29:36.035
- Mr. Booker.

29:36.078 --> 29:37.645
I understand wanting
to move on.

29:37.688 --> 29:40.691
To pack up everything that
reminds you of your wife

29:40.735 --> 29:42.345
and put it in boxes.

29:42.389 --> 29:44.304
But that is not
what Hanna needs.

29:44.347 --> 29:47.089
- I think we've been over this.
I know what my daughter needs.

29:47.133 --> 29:49.265
- With all due respect,

29:49.309 --> 29:52.268
right now...
I don't think you do.

29:52.312 --> 29:54.793
- Miles--
- Dad, please. Please.

29:54.836 --> 29:56.446
Just let me finish.

29:56.490 --> 29:58.535
♪

29:58.579 --> 30:00.581
I can't put myself
in your shoes,

30:00.624 --> 30:03.105
but I've been in hers.

30:03.149 --> 30:04.890
I know what she's feeling.

30:04.933 --> 30:06.979
And right now,
more than anything else,

30:07.022 --> 30:09.285
she is desperate
to remember her mother.

30:09.329 --> 30:10.678
- What are you talking about?

30:10.721 --> 30:15.988
♪

30:16.031 --> 30:17.859
- You wife's?

30:17.903 --> 30:19.513
- Yes.

30:19.556 --> 30:21.384
Where'd you get that?

30:21.428 --> 30:25.562
- I found it in one of the
boxes that you were donating.

30:25.606 --> 30:30.132
This was the same perfume that
Hanna was caught shoplifting.

30:30.176 --> 30:33.440
♪

30:33.483 --> 30:36.791
She doesn't want to move.

30:36.835 --> 30:40.099
She doesn't want to run away
from the pain.

30:40.142 --> 30:41.927
You do.

30:41.970 --> 30:43.624
♪

30:43.667 --> 30:46.018
What Hanna needs right now

30:46.061 --> 30:49.108
is to know that she is not
in this alone.

30:49.151 --> 30:52.024
That she has someone
that she can talk to

30:52.067 --> 30:54.330
to remember her mother with.

30:54.374 --> 30:56.419
♪

30:56.463 --> 31:00.380
If you don't open up
to her now,

31:00.423 --> 31:04.253
you'll both wake up 15 years
later wishing you had...

31:04.297 --> 31:05.864
♪

31:05.907 --> 31:09.084
And realizing that you can
never get that time back.

31:09.128 --> 31:16.135
♪

31:26.101 --> 31:28.974
- ♪ Save your breath,
my brother ♪

31:29.017 --> 31:31.890
♪ It's not going in

31:31.933 --> 31:34.849
♪ I'm not your disciple

31:34.893 --> 31:37.504
♪ I choose how I sin

31:37.547 --> 31:40.246
- Just tell her how you feel.

31:40.289 --> 31:42.030
- It's been a while.

31:42.074 --> 31:44.337
Not sure how I remember
how anymore.

31:44.380 --> 31:46.817
- Speak from the heart.
You'll be fine.

31:46.861 --> 31:52.084
- ♪ You don't know me
like you used to ♪

31:52.127 --> 31:55.870
♪ You can leave,
but I refuse to ♪

31:55.914 --> 32:02.790
♪

32:07.664 --> 32:09.928
- I haven't been listening
very good, have I?

32:11.842 --> 32:13.583
You don't want to move.

32:15.977 --> 32:17.413
- No.

32:18.719 --> 32:20.373
- Why didn't you tell me?

32:20.416 --> 32:22.853
- Because I knew you wanted to.

32:25.160 --> 32:26.857
- Yeah.

32:27.946 --> 32:30.165
I just didn't realize why
until today.

32:41.046 --> 32:43.787
Did you know that I first
bought that for your mom

32:43.831 --> 32:46.529
the day we found out
we were having you?

32:46.573 --> 32:49.010
- No.

32:49.054 --> 32:50.664
Mom never told me.

32:51.839 --> 32:54.929
- I can remember it
like it was yesterday.

32:54.973 --> 32:57.932
The smile across her face
when we heard the news.

32:57.976 --> 33:00.239
♪

33:00.282 --> 33:03.111
She always wanted a girl.

33:03.155 --> 33:04.983
So did I.

33:05.026 --> 33:10.727
♪

33:10.771 --> 33:12.860
I miss her so much.

33:14.688 --> 33:17.038
- Me too.

33:17.082 --> 33:23.044
♪

33:25.046 --> 33:28.702
- I'm so sorry I made you feel
like you had to forget her.

33:28.745 --> 33:31.096
You don't.

33:31.139 --> 33:34.055
And luckily, neither do I.

33:34.099 --> 33:38.538
Because I have the most amazing
reminder of her.

33:38.581 --> 33:39.713
- What?

33:39.756 --> 33:41.541
♪

33:41.584 --> 33:42.977
- You.

33:43.021 --> 33:50.028
♪

34:10.135 --> 34:12.572
- So you think this Henry Chase
guy is behind the God Account?

34:12.615 --> 34:14.139
- Mm-hmm.

34:14.182 --> 34:15.227
- And this article you tracked
down might help you find him?

34:15.270 --> 34:16.706
- Mm-hmm.

34:18.317 --> 34:20.580
- You two are phenomenal
conversationalists,

34:20.623 --> 34:22.321
you know that?

34:22.364 --> 34:24.453
- Sorry.
It's--

34:24.497 --> 34:25.846
Okay, listen to this.

34:25.889 --> 34:27.543
In the article,
Henry talks about

34:27.587 --> 34:31.591
wanting to use technology
to explore humanity.

34:31.634 --> 34:33.114
To bring us together.

34:33.158 --> 34:35.464
- It's almost like he's talking
about the God Account.

34:35.508 --> 34:37.858
- He alludes to some tragedy
that happened in his life

34:37.901 --> 34:39.816
but never gets specific.

34:39.860 --> 34:41.644
Maybe what happened
has something to do

34:41.688 --> 34:44.125
with why he's helping
people now.

34:44.169 --> 34:46.432
He's trying to correct
the past.

34:46.475 --> 34:48.347
- Then why not come forward?

34:48.390 --> 34:50.479
You know, why hide
for the last ten years?

34:50.523 --> 34:51.741
- Maybe he was waiting.

34:51.785 --> 34:53.352
- For what?

34:53.395 --> 34:54.875
- To find the right person
for the God Account.

34:56.746 --> 34:58.444
- Miles.

34:58.487 --> 35:00.533
♪

35:00.576 --> 35:02.230
- Okay,
let's say you're right.

35:02.274 --> 35:04.319
Then why not introduce himself?

35:04.363 --> 35:06.669
Or--or at least leave
some clues on how to find him?

35:06.713 --> 35:08.758
♪

35:08.802 --> 35:11.805
- Maybe he has,

35:11.848 --> 35:14.590
Uh, I need to go.
I need to get to my computer.

35:14.634 --> 35:16.984
I'll--I'll text you later.
Um...

35:17.027 --> 35:19.508
Have a good trip.

35:19.552 --> 35:21.380
- Where are you going?

35:21.423 --> 35:25.123
- Uh, Vermont with Eli.

35:25.166 --> 35:26.428
- You don't sound sure.

35:26.472 --> 35:30.998
♪

35:31.041 --> 35:33.305
You said the God Account
might be about Falken

35:33.348 --> 35:35.829
trying to correct something
from his past, right?

35:35.872 --> 35:37.396
- Yeah.

35:37.439 --> 35:39.180
- You ever think that that's
what you might be trying

35:39.224 --> 35:41.313
to do with Eli?

35:41.356 --> 35:47.057
♪

35:47.101 --> 35:48.885
- What are we doing back here?

35:51.323 --> 35:54.761
- I've been thinking a lot
about what you said to me.

35:54.804 --> 35:56.589
It was, uh,

35:56.632 --> 35:59.679
hard to hear.
- [sighs]

35:59.722 --> 36:02.682
I know. I'm sorry.
- No, don't be. You were right.

36:02.725 --> 36:07.208
What Aaron was doing,
trying to run from his pain,

36:07.252 --> 36:10.472
not deal with his loss.
I didn't see it.

36:10.516 --> 36:13.214
Not because it was foreign
to me,

36:13.258 --> 36:15.564
but because it was
so damn familiar.

36:18.785 --> 36:22.223
I wasn't there for you
like you needed me to be.

36:22.267 --> 36:24.182
♪

36:24.225 --> 36:29.578
As a parent, all you want is
to protect your kids from pain.

36:29.622 --> 36:30.797
I mean, when you and Ali
were little

36:30.840 --> 36:32.015
and you hurt yourself--

36:32.059 --> 36:33.713
skin you knee
or bumped your head,

36:33.756 --> 36:37.064
anything small--if I could get
to you fast enough

36:37.107 --> 36:38.587
and catch you
before you started crying

36:38.631 --> 36:40.241
and tell you everything's
gonna be okay--

36:40.285 --> 36:42.678
"You're gonna be okay"--

36:42.722 --> 36:45.203
More often than not,

36:45.246 --> 36:48.162
you'd believe me.

36:48.206 --> 36:50.556
You mother...

36:50.599 --> 36:52.775
never tried to convince you
of anything.

36:52.819 --> 36:53.907
She'd just--

36:53.950 --> 36:55.778
- Listen.
- Mm-hmm.

36:55.822 --> 36:59.652
♪

36:59.695 --> 37:01.741
Not a day does by
that I don't

37:01.784 --> 37:04.613
wake up thinking of her.

37:04.657 --> 37:06.833
- Me too.

37:06.876 --> 37:10.663
- Your mother used to say that
anything that makes you smile

37:10.706 --> 37:12.404
is God.

37:12.447 --> 37:14.449
In all my years
as a reverend,

37:14.493 --> 37:18.279
I haven't heard a better
description of what I believe.

37:18.323 --> 37:23.066
Now, I have no idea
who's behind the God Account

37:23.110 --> 37:25.286
or why they chose you,

37:25.330 --> 37:29.072
but when I saw that smile
on Hanna's face today...

37:29.116 --> 37:31.205
♪

37:31.249 --> 37:34.817
It's hard not to see God
in that.

37:34.861 --> 37:41.868
♪

37:45.524 --> 37:48.091
- So what, we're just gonna
head back?

37:48.135 --> 37:49.658
- Not quite yet.

37:49.702 --> 37:51.225
What do you say?

37:51.269 --> 37:54.228
[upbeat music]

37:54.272 --> 37:55.708
- [chuckles]

37:55.751 --> 37:57.144
- Well, I'm sure
you're tall enough.

37:57.187 --> 38:01.104
♪

38:01.148 --> 38:06.284
- ♪ I hope someday
we'll sit down together ♪

38:06.327 --> 38:09.330
- Most people say
you can't go back in time.

38:09.374 --> 38:12.464
That there is no way to correct
the mistakes of our past.

38:12.507 --> 38:13.943
[chuckles]

38:13.987 --> 38:15.989
The past is a funny thing.

38:16.032 --> 38:19.949
The only power it has over us
is what we choose to give it.

38:19.993 --> 38:21.777
When we let go of it,

38:21.821 --> 38:23.823
we let go of the expectations
that come with it.

38:23.866 --> 38:25.041
The need to correct it.

38:25.085 --> 38:26.347
- Hey.

38:26.391 --> 38:28.784
♪

38:28.828 --> 38:30.917
I can't go.

38:30.960 --> 38:32.701
- Yeah, I kinda got that.

38:32.745 --> 38:35.269
- When we ran into each other
on the street that night...

38:35.313 --> 38:37.227
♪

38:37.271 --> 38:39.839
I don't know,
it felt like fate.

38:39.882 --> 38:42.407
And we both had changed
so much,

38:42.450 --> 38:45.235
maybe we owed it to ourselves
to try again.

38:45.279 --> 38:47.150
- I still want to.
- I know.

38:47.194 --> 38:50.502
And I thought I did too.

38:50.545 --> 38:52.112
But the thing is I--

38:52.155 --> 38:54.419
I don't think we changed
so we can get back together.

38:54.462 --> 38:56.203
♪

38:56.246 --> 39:00.207
I think we changed so
we could keep moving forward.

39:00.250 --> 39:02.731
And I need to keep doing that.

39:02.775 --> 39:05.691
- Yeah, I think you do too.

39:05.734 --> 39:11.087
But if you're being completely
honest with yourself,

39:11.131 --> 39:13.394
are you sure
this isn't about Miles?

39:13.438 --> 39:16.397
♪

39:16.441 --> 39:18.225
- Yeah.

39:18.268 --> 39:20.401
Yeah, I'm sure.
It's about me.

39:20.445 --> 39:24.013
♪

39:24.057 --> 39:26.146
Bye, Eli.

39:26.189 --> 39:29.410
- See you around, Cara.

39:29.454 --> 39:32.195
- ♪ Yeah, I know
it ain't pretty ♪

39:32.239 --> 39:36.243
♪ When two hearts
get broke ♪

39:36.286 --> 39:40.552
- The past will always be
a part of who we are.

39:40.595 --> 39:45.078
It's how we feel about it
moving forward that matters.

39:45.121 --> 39:47.602
- Sorry, I know that taking
all this stuff back home

39:47.646 --> 39:49.430
isn't very charitable.
- [chuckles]

39:49.474 --> 39:50.736
- How's Hanna doing?

39:50.779 --> 39:52.215
- She's good, she's good.

39:52.259 --> 39:55.044
Back in school.
Has a smile on her face again.

39:55.088 --> 39:56.437
I want to thank you both
for that.

39:56.481 --> 39:59.440
- Well, I'm glad
that we could help.

39:59.484 --> 40:06.447
♪

40:06.491 --> 40:07.883
- Does it get any easier?

40:07.927 --> 40:09.972
♪

40:10.016 --> 40:12.453
I mean, do you ever
stop missing them?

40:12.497 --> 40:14.977
- No,
but why would you want to?

40:15.021 --> 40:17.023
♪

40:17.066 --> 40:19.895
- Thanks, Arthur.

40:19.939 --> 40:22.028
- Sometimes it's as simple

40:22.071 --> 40:25.118
as replacing one memory
with another.

40:25.161 --> 40:30.210
- ♪ I hope someday,
we'll sit down together ♪

40:30.253 --> 40:33.692
♪ And laugh with each other
about these days ♪

40:33.735 --> 40:38.653
- Or finding some small way
to carry it with us.

40:38.697 --> 40:41.351
And while I know
you can't go back in time

40:41.395 --> 40:43.136
and correct the past,

40:43.179 --> 40:45.355
sometimes you can get
pretty close.

40:45.399 --> 40:48.097
- ♪ Ohh, ooh, ooh, ooh

40:48.141 --> 40:50.143
♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh

40:50.186 --> 40:53.059
♪ Ohh, ooh, ooh, ooh

40:53.102 --> 40:55.278
♪ These days, these days

40:55.322 --> 40:58.238
♪ Ohh, ooh, ooh, ooh

40:58.281 --> 41:00.501
♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh

41:00.545 --> 41:03.504
♪ Ohh, ooh, ooh, ooh

41:03.548 --> 41:06.507
♪ These days, these days

41:06.551 --> 41:10.642
♪ We wish we could come back
to these days, these days ♪

41:10.685 --> 41:13.993
♪ Yeah, we wish we could
come back to these days ♪

41:14.036 --> 41:15.298
[knocking on door]

41:15.342 --> 41:16.822
♪ These days, these days

41:18.258 --> 41:20.042
[knocking continues]

41:21.000 --> 41:23.132
- Hey, you said you figured
something out. What is it?

41:23.176 --> 41:25.047
- After reading the article
on Henry Chase,

41:25.091 --> 41:26.440
I started thinking

41:26.484 --> 41:29.051
what if we already have
everything we need

41:29.095 --> 41:30.531
in order to find Falken?

41:30.575 --> 41:32.794
What if he's already given
all the pieces to us?

41:32.838 --> 41:34.317
- What do you mean?
- Well,

41:34.361 --> 41:35.884
I started inputting
all the coordinates

41:35.928 --> 41:37.495
of all the Friend Suggestions
we've gotten,

41:37.538 --> 41:40.236
and all the places and events
associated with them,

41:40.280 --> 41:42.761
we have John Dove
and the subway,

41:42.804 --> 41:43.979
Cara and the park bench,

41:44.023 --> 41:45.503
Katie and Nate
in Central Park.

41:45.546 --> 41:48.418
We got Hayden Planetarium,
Grand Central,

41:48.462 --> 41:51.160
Sal's brownstone,
the chess shop, all of it.

41:51.204 --> 41:52.901
- And?

41:52.945 --> 41:54.294
- Check this out.

41:54.337 --> 41:56.122
♪

41:56.165 --> 41:59.125
[beeping]

41:59.168 --> 42:06.175
♪

42:10.789 --> 42:12.051
[beeping]

42:13.052 --> 42:14.662
- A Fibonacci Spiral.

42:14.706 --> 42:16.272
- It's like everything
we've been doing

42:16.316 --> 42:17.404
has already
been predicted.

42:17.447 --> 42:18.840
- That's impossible.

42:18.884 --> 42:21.495
- And yet, not.

42:22.627 --> 42:24.324
Predictive analytics,
remember?

42:24.367 --> 42:26.282
- Yeah, it looks like
the spiral isn't complete yet.

42:26.326 --> 42:27.849
- Uh, it's not but it's close.

42:27.893 --> 42:29.459
The center just needs
a few more data points

42:29.503 --> 42:31.505
in order to match
the golden ratio.

42:31.549 --> 42:33.333
- You mean Friend Suggestions.

42:33.376 --> 42:37.119
- Mm-hmm. Well, if my
calculations are correct,

42:37.163 --> 42:40.383
our next Friend Suggestion
will complete the spiral

42:40.427 --> 42:42.560
and pinpoint the location.

42:42.603 --> 42:44.866
- For what?

42:44.910 --> 42:46.694
- Falken.

42:47.652 --> 42:50.611
[suspenseful music]

42:50.655 --> 42:53.266
♪

43:21.990 --> 43:22.991
- Greg, move your head!
